{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"45"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/45"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.28,0.67,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"45"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56856"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/45"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"45"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42309"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"123"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56856"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of persistent and intensifying pain in her right leg that intermittently disrupts her sleep. The discomfort was initially attributed to a previous netball-related injury. However, it has not improved despite simple analgesia and rest. She has a medical history of asthma and takes fluticasone via daily inhaler and salbutamol as needed. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is restricted movement and notable tenderness immediately above the right knee. Laboratory investigations reveal a normal white blood cell count and an elevated alkaline phosphatase level. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hodgkin lymphoma","Ewing sarcoma","Osteosarcoma","Bony metastases","Infectious osteomyelitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic localised pain in the right thigh, accompanied by X-ray findings suggestive of a destructive and irritative bone lesion, with lytic and blastic lesions and new bone formation. The presence of a Codman triangle-type periosteal reaction indicates an aggressive lesion where new layers fail to ossify fully, resulting in the characteristic triangular shape. These changes are characteristic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary bone tumours are rare, accounting for less than 0.2% of all cancers and approximately 6% of childhood cancers. In adolescents, these tumours typically occur spontaneously, while in adults, bone sarcomas are often associated with Paget\u0027s disease or radiation therapy. Diagnosis is confirmed through bone biopsy, preferably conducted in a specialist unit due to the complexity of management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHodgkin lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with constitutional symptoms such as fever, night sweats, and weight loss, along with evidence of lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, skin infiltrations, pulmonary findings, and neurological signs\u2014all absent in this case. X-rays of patients with Hodgkin lymphoma would show enlarged lymph nodes rather than bone lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEwing sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E, another rare bone malignancy, commonly arises from the long bones of the extremities. While chronic localised pain and tenderness are typical presentations, Ewing sarcoma is also accompanied by systemic symptoms like fever, fatigue, and weight loss, which are lacking in this case. Additionally, X-rays of Ewing sarcoma patients often reveal bone lesions in the diaphysis region of long bones, which is not evident here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBony metastases\u003C/strong\u003E, a common manifestation of distant cancer relapse, typically involve areas of red marrow such as the skull, axial skeleton, or the medullary portion of the appendicular skeleton\u2014none of which are relevant to this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious osteomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with acute symptoms including fever, localised warmth, redness, and swelling over the affected bone, often accompanied by systemic symptoms like malaise and chills. However, there are no precipitating factors suggestive of infectious osteomyelitis in this case. Radiological findings for infectious osteomyelitis include nonspecific indicators such as periosteal reaction, bone destruction, or soft tissue swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary tumours of the bone are rare, comprising less than 0.2% of all cancers and about 6% of all childhood cancers.","Osteosarcoma typically presents with chronic localised pain and characteristic X-ray findings including lytic and blastic lesions, new bone formation, and Codman triangle periosteal reaction."],"references":["Green NM, Abas S, Sajid S, Cribb GL. Presentation of bone tumours: clinical findings and initial management of patients. Orthopaedics and Trauma [Internet]. 2021 June [cited 2024 March 15];35(3):108-114. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mporth.2021.03.001","\u200cSingla A, Geller DS. Musculoskeletal Tumors. Pediatr Clin N Am 2020; 67:227-45. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31779834/","\u200cZheng YF, Lin J, Yang HL. Chondroblastic osteosarcoma secondary to fibrosarcoma: A case report and literature review. Oncology Letters. 2015 Oct 12;10(6):3573\u20136. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4665868/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42309"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"45"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20586"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20586"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vdaIUum4YKqCN5BIKppqYSyKKAbQkA.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/vdaIUum4YKqCN5BIKppqYSyKKAbQkA.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":754,"height":1249}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42309"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T10:04:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T10:40:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"45"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56856"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id